@NODE Introducing "Introducing IconTrace"
@TOC Main

       IconTrace is a program that allows you to monitor what the
     icon library is doing when you start a program using the
     Workbench.  It's main use lies in discovering undocumented
     ToolTypes and debugging your existing ToolTypes by watching if
     the program finds them allright.  You are also shown what icons
     your programs look for.  

       IconTrace software and documentation are copyright ˋ 1993 by
     Peter Stuer.  All rights reserved.  

@ENDNODE

@NODE Requirements "System Requirements"
@TOC Main

       IconTrace should run on any Amiga system with at least 512K RAM
     and one disk-drive.  IconTrace requires KickStart v2.04 or higher
     to run.  Special care has been taken in the program design to
     make the program work with 68020, 68030 and 68040 processors
     without sacrificing 68000 compatibility.  

       Should you have any trouble running IconTrace on your machine,
     please write to me with the full specifications of your machine,
     that is KickStart version, model, expansion boards etc...  

       IconTrace is KickStart 3.0 compatible and aware.  It will show
     you some of the new features available with this version of the
     operating system.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Usage "Usage"
@TOC Main

       IconTrace can be started from the Shell or the Workbench.  

       To start IconTrace from the Shell simply type: 

             1> IconTrace 

     followed by a return.  This loads the IconTrace program and
     starts it.  IconTrace will then open its window and will start
     monitoring AmigaDOS.  By default IconTrace will open a window
     that is as wide and as high as the default public screen (most
     of the times, the Workbench screen) without overlapping the
     title bar.  

       If you run IconTrace with a questionmark (?) as argument you'll
     get the argument template: 

             OUTPUT: 

       If you want the output to appear somewhere else simply add a
     filename or device specification after the command: 

             1> IconTrace PRT: 

     will send all output to the printer. To save the output to a
     file: 

             1> IconTrace RAM:SomeFile 

       To start IconTrace from the Workbench, simply click on the
     accompanying icon and IconTrace starts.  

       Adding the OUTPUT tooltype to the IconTrace icon will have the
     same effect as with Shell usage: 

             OUTPUT=CON:/18//300/IconTrace 

     will open a console window at position (0,18) that is the full
     with of the Workbench screen and 300 lines high.  

       You can also use the Execute Command item from the Workbench
     menu to run IconTrace.  

       The output can be stopped at any time by pressing Control-C.  

@ENDNODE

@NODE Output "About the output"
@TOC Main

       Currently the following functions are monitored: 

             FindToolType 
             GetDiskObject 
             GetDiskObjectNew 
             GetDefDiskObject 
             MatchToolValue 
             PutDiskObject 
             PutDefDiskObject 

       The information shown depends on which function is being
     traced but all messages have 3 components in common: 

             Process Name    The name of the process calling the 
                             AmigaDOS function.  

             Trace Info      Verbose information about the function 
                             being executed.  

             Result          Whether the call was succesfull or not 
                             (if applicable) 

@ENDNODE

